## Introduction
You can control entity movement while a player is riding, such as horses or custom mounts.

### Example: Controlling Horse Movement
```java
@EventHandler
public void onPlayerMove(PlayerMoveEvent event) {
    Player player = event.getPlayer();
    if(player.getVehicle() instanceof Horse horse) {
        horse.setCustomName("§6Speedy Horse");
        // You can modify speed, jump strength, etc.
        horse.setJumpStrength(0.7);
        horse.setAI(true);
    }
}
```

### Logic Explanation
- `getVehicle()` returns the entity the player is riding.
- Horse attributes like speed and jump can be modified.
- AI can be toggled for autonomous behavior when needed.

### Edge Cases & Warnings
- Some entities ignore AI or speed modifications.
- Avoid applying heavy logic every tick; may cause lag.
- Always check `instanceof` to prevent ClassCastException.

## Introduction
Create custom mounts with special effects, attributes, or invisibility for unique gameplay experiences.

### Example: Invisible Mount with Firework Effects
```java
Horse horse = player.getWorld().spawn(player.getLocation(), Horse.class);
horse.setInvisible(true);
horse.addPassenger(player);
// Add repeating effect
Bukkit.getScheduler().runTaskTimer(plugin, () -> {
    horse.getWorld().spawnParticle(Particle.FLAME, horse.getLocation(), 5);
}, 0L, 5L);
```

### Logic Explanation
- `setInvisible(true)` hides the mount visually.
- Scheduled tasks can add continuous particle effects.
- This allows creative mounts like flying mounts or visual illusions.

### Edge Cases & Warnings
- Invisible mounts still interact with collisions.
- Be cautious with scheduled tasks to avoid server lag.
- Removing the mount should clean up particles and tasks.
